   117	\title{The Univalent Correspondence: \\
   118	How Six Perspectives on Number Become One \\
   119	\large Synthesis of the Univalent Correspondence Series}
   120	
   121	\author{YonedaAI Research \\
   122	\textit{Univalent Correspondence Project} \\
   123	\textit{Synthesis paper for the six topical papers (I--VI)} \\
   124	\texttt{research@yonedaai.example}}
   125	
   126	\date{3 May 2026}
   127	
   128	\begin{document}
   129	\maketitle
   130	
   131	\begin{abstract}
   132	This is the synthesis paper for the six-part series \emph{The Univalent
   133	Correspondence}. Each topical paper takes one perspective on the question
   134	``what is the natural number $58$?'' and develops it to maturity: Paper~I
   135	treats $58$ naively as a symbol or quantity; Paper~II encodes it
   136	set-theoretically as a von Neumann ordinal; Paper~III characterizes it by a
   137	universal property as the $58$th iterate of $\suc$ in any initial successor
   138	structure; Paper~IV identifies it with its representable functor
   139	$\Hom(-, 58)$; Paper~V realises it as a canonical term of an inductive type
   140	$\N$ in Homotopy Type Theory, identified up to path equivalence; Paper~VI
   141	reads it structurally, as an invariant under all structure-preserving
   142	morphisms between models of arithmetic. We argue that under Voevodsky's
   143	univalence axiom, the four perspectives of Papers~III through~VI are not
   144	analogous but \emph{literally identical}: an initial successor structure, a
   145	representing presheaf, a contractible $\Sigma$-type of NNO structures, and a
   146	structural invariant of arithmetic models are four faces of one
   147	$\infty$-groupoid. We name this identification the \emph{univalent
   148	correspondence}, building on the four-way computational tetrad of Curry,
   149	Howard, Lambek, and Voevodsky (extending Wadler's
   150	propositions-as-types-as-spaces and Harper's computational trinity). After
   151	reviewing each level, motivating the canonical six-row table, and making the
   152	unifying $\infty$-groupoid framework precise, we prove transit theorems
   153	showing that each level transcends its predecessor: the set-theoretic level
   154	resolves the naive symbol/object confusion but introduces
   155	encoding-relativity (Benacerraf's identification problem); the universal
   156	property resolves encoding by going relational; Yoneda makes ``relational
   157	profile'' mathematically precise as a representable functor; HoTT makes
   158	Yoneda's ``iff'' into a literal identity in the universe via univalence;
   159	and the categorical/structural perspective is the philosophical commitment
   160	that \emph{all of this} is what mathematical objects are. We close with a
   161	research outlook on ContextFS / typed memory as a structural-identity
   162	primitive, transcendentals $\pi$ and $e$ in HoTT via Cauchy reals as a
   163	higher inductive--inductive type, directed HoTT and synthetic
   164	$\infty$-category theory, and the principal open problem: a synthetic
   165	foundation for analytic number theory.
   166	\end{abstract}
   167	
   168	\tableofcontents
   169	\bigskip
   170	
   171	\section{Introduction}
   172	\label{sec:intro}
   173	
   174	\subsection{The question and the six perspectives}
   175	
   176	The Univalent Correspondence series asks one question --- \emph{what is the
   177	natural number $58$?} --- and answers it six different ways. The six papers
   178	of the series each occupy one row of \cref{tab:six-rows}, the central
   179	organizing artifact of the project. The synthesis paper before you argues
   180	that the rightmost four rows describe the \emph{same} mathematical object,
   181	identified up to equivalence by Voevodsky's univalence axiom.
   182	
   183	\begin{table}[ht]
   184	\centering
   185	\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{l X}
   186	\toprule
   187	\textbf{Level (Paper)} & \textbf{What $58$ is at this level} \\
   188	\midrule
   189	Naive (I) & A symbol on the page; a quantity counted by a finger or scratch. \\
   190	Set-theoretic (II) & The von Neumann ordinal $\{0, 1, \ldots, 57\}$; equivalently, any iso-class of ZFC encodings of the same Peano structure. \\
   191	Universal property (III) & The $58$-th iterate $\suc^{58}(\zero)$ in \emph{any} initial successor structure $(N, 0, \suc)$ in any category with terminal object. \\
   192	Yoneda (IV) & The representable functor $\Hom(-, 58)$ on the appropriate category; equivalently, the entire system of probes that land on $58$. \\
   193	HoTT (V) & A canonical term in the inductive type $\N$, identified up to path equivalence (and hence, by univalence, identified across NNO presentations). \\
   194	Categorical / structural (VI) & A semantic invariant, in the sense of Awodey, Resnik, and Shapiro, under all structure-preserving morphisms between models of arithmetic. \\
   195	\bottomrule
   196	\end{tabularx}
   197	\caption{The six perspectives on the natural number $58$. Rows~III--VI
   198	become literally identical under the univalence axiom (\cref{sec:transit}).}
   199	\label{tab:six-rows}
   200	\end{table}
   201	
   202	The series is not a survey. Each topical paper is a self-contained
   203	mathematical development with its own theorems, proofs, and Haskell
   204	artifacts. Paper~I~\cite{paper-i} is historical and philosophical, anchoring
   205	the discussion in numerals and counting; Paper~II~\cite{paper-ii}
   206	axiomatizes ZFC, develops the von Neumann hierarchy, and proves Benacerraf's
   207	identification problem in formal terms; Paper~III~\cite{paper-iii}
   208	introduces the natural numbers object, derives primitive recursion from its
   209	universal property, and shows the equivalence with second-order Peano
   210	arithmetic; Paper~IV~\cite{paper-iv} proves the Yoneda lemma in covariant
   211	and contravariant forms, with applications to numbers, groups, schemes, and
   212	the $\infty$-categorical generalization; Paper~V~\cite{paper-v} is a
   213	self-contained development of HoTT including identity types, path
   214	induction, the univalence axiom, higher inductive types, and the cubical
   215	realisation; Paper~VI~\cite{paper-vi} surveys mathematical structuralism,
   216	proves an isomorphism-invariance theorem for first-order properties, and
   217	relates categorification to decategorification.
   218	
   219	The synthesis paper before you assumes the existence and content of these
   220	six topical papers and combines them. We do not re-prove their main
   221	theorems; we cite them. What we do prove are the \emph{transit theorems}
   222	between levels, and we collect them into a single mathematical statement of
   223	the univalent correspondence (\cref{sec:transit,sec:correspondence}).
   224	
   225	\subsection{The thesis}
   226	
   227	The thesis of this paper, and of the series as a whole, has two layers.
   228	
   229	\begin{principle}[Univalent Correspondence, weak form]
   230	\label{prin:weak}
   231	For the natural numbers, and more generally for any mathematical
   232	structure presentable by an essentially algebraic theory, the four
   233	perspectives \emph{universal property} (Paper~III), \emph{Yoneda}
   234	(Paper~IV), \emph{HoTT term up to path equivalence} (Paper~V), and
   235	\emph{structural invariant} (Paper~VI) yield equivalent characterisations.
   236	\end{principle}
   237	
   238	\begin{principle}[Univalent Correspondence, strong form]
   239	\label{prin:strong}
   240	Under the univalence axiom, the equivalences of \cref{prin:weak} are
   241	internalised as identities in a universe $\U$. The four characterisations
   242	do not merely yield isomorphic answers; they are paths in the same
   243	$\infty$-groupoid, and the natural number $58$ is a single point in that
   244	$\infty$-groupoid, viewed through four windows.
   245	\end{principle}
   246	
   247	The strong form is the content of \cref{thm:identity-of-perspectives}
   248	below. The weak form is established meta-theoretically by the work of
   249	Lawvere~\cite{Lawvere1964}, Lambek~\cite{Lambek1972}, Wadler~\cite{Wadler2015},
   250	Awodey~\cite{Awodey2014}, and the HoTT Book~\cite{HoTTBook}. The strong
   251	form requires univalence and the structure identity principle (SIP); see
   252	\cref{sec:transit-vi}.
   253	
   254	\subsection{Why a sixth row?}
   255	
   256	A natural question: if the universal property already characterises $58$ up
   257	to canonical isomorphism, why do we need Yoneda, HoTT, and the structural
   258	view as separate rows? The short answer: each row resolves a residual
   259	question raised by the previous one.
   260	
   261	\begin{itemize}
   262	\item \textbf{Naive (I) $\to$ Set-theoretic (II).} The naive level confuses
   263	the symbol $58$ with the number $58$. The set-theoretic level resolves the
   264	confusion by exhibiting a definite mathematical object
   265	$\{0, 1, \ldots, 57\}$.
   266	\item \textbf{Set-theoretic (II) $\to$ Universal property (III).} The
   267	set-theoretic encoding is non-canonical (Benacerraf): von Neumann's and
   268	Zermelo's encodings disagree about whether $\{\emptyset\} \in 17$. The
   269	universal property abstracts away from the encoding by characterising the
   270	structure up to canonical isomorphism.
   271	\item \textbf{Universal property (III) $\to$ Yoneda (IV).} Universal
   272	properties give a relational identification one structure at a time. The
   273	Yoneda lemma generalises this to a universal principle: \emph{every} object
   274	is determined by its system of incoming morphisms. ``$58$ is initial-among-X''
   275	becomes ``$58$ \emph{is} the functor $\Hom(-, 58)$.''
   276	\item \textbf{Yoneda (IV) $\to$ HoTT (V).} The Yoneda lemma yields
   277	$X \iso Y \iff h_X \iso h_Y$ as a meta-theorem about a category. Under
   278	univalence, this ``iff'' becomes a literal equality in the universe: the
   279	implication $h_X = h_Y \to X = Y$ is constructed by transport, and the
   280	implication $X \iso Y \to X = Y$ is the univalence axiom.
   281	\item \textbf{HoTT (V) $\to$ Categorical/Structural (VI).} HoTT is a formal
   282	system. The categorical/structural view is the philosophical commitment
   283	that \emph{this is what mathematical objects are}: positions in structures,
   284	identified up to equivalence-respecting morphisms. SIP makes this
   285	philosophical commitment provable inside HoTT.
   286	\end{itemize}
   287	
   288	\subsection{Naming the correspondence}
   289	
   290	The four rightmost rows of \cref{tab:six-rows} correspond to the four
   291	columns of the \emph{computational tetrad}, the four-way extension of the
   292	Curry--Howard--Lambek correspondence shown in \cref{tab:tetrad}. We follow
   293	Wadler~\cite{Wadler2015} in calling its central insight
   294	\emph{propositions-as-types-as-spaces}, but we call its strong form
   295	(internalised by the univalence axiom) \emph{the univalent correspondence}.
   296	The terminology and its history are surveyed in \cref{sec:naming}.
   297	
   298	\begin{table}[ht]
   299	\centering
   300	\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{X X X X}
   301	\toprule
   302	\textbf{Logic} & \textbf{Type theory} & \textbf{Category theory} &
   303	\textbf{Homotopy / topology} \\
   304	\midrule
   305	Propositions & Types & Objects & Spaces \\
   306	Proofs & Terms & Morphisms & Points / paths \\
   307	Implication $A \to B$ & Function type $A \to B$ & Hom-set & Path space \\
   308	Conjunction $A \wedge B$ & Product $A \times B$ & Product / limit & --- \\
   309	Disjunction $A \vee B$ & Sum $A + B$ & Coproduct / colimit & --- \\
   310	Truth $\top$ & Unit $\mathbf{1}$ & Terminal object & Point \\
   311	Falsehood $\bot$ & Empty $\mathbf{0}$ & Initial object & Empty space \\
   312	Equality $a = b$ & Identity $\Id_A(a, b)$ & Isomorphism & Homotopy equivalence \\
   313	Universal $\forall$ & $\Pi$-type & Right adjoint / limit & Fibration \\
   314	Existential $\exists$ & $\Sigma$-type & Left adjoint / colimit & Total space \\
   315	\bottomrule
   316	\end{tabularx}
   317	\caption{The computational tetrad. Each row is a single concept seen
   318	through four windows. Adapted from~\cite{Wadler2015,HoTTBook}; the
   319	explicit fourth column is due to Voevodsky's univalent foundations
   320	project.}
   321	\label{tab:tetrad}
   322	\end{table}
   323	
   324	\subsection{Outline}
   325	
   326	\Cref{sec:row-by-row} reviews the six perspectives row by row, summarising
   327	the principal results of Papers~I through~VI. \Cref{sec:transit} proves the
   328	five transit theorems that move from one level to the next.
   329	\Cref{sec:framework} sets up the unified mathematical framework: an
   330	$\infty$-groupoid model under univalence, in which the four rightmost
   331	perspectives correspond to four functors out of one $\infty$-topos.
   332	\Cref{sec:correspondence} states and proves the main identity-of-perspectives
   333	theorem. \Cref{sec:diagrams} makes the inter-level commutativity precise via
   334	commutative diagrams of equivalences. \Cref{sec:naming} surveys the history
   335	of the naming and explains our preference for ``the univalent
   336	correspondence.'' \Cref{sec:applications} sketches three downstream
   337	applications: ContextFS as a structural-identity computational primitive,
   338	transcendentals $\pi$ and $e$ in HoTT, and directed HoTT for representation
   339	theory. \Cref{sec:open} collects open problems. \Cref{sec:conclusion}
   340	concludes.
   341	
   342	\section{Row by Row: The Six Perspectives in Brief}
   343	\label{sec:row-by-row}
   344	
   345	This section is a synopsis of the six topical papers. We assume the reader
   346	has access to the topical papers and reproduce only enough material to
   347	make the synthesis self-contained.
   348	
   349	\subsection{Paper I: Naive --- numbers as symbols and quantities}
   350	\label{sec:row-i}
   351	
   352	Paper~I~\cite{paper-i} occupies the pre-formal level. A natural number $58$
   353	is, at this level, a symbol on a page (``$58$''), a Roman numeral
   354	(\textsf{LVIII}), a tally (fifty-eight scratches), or a Babylonian
   355	sexagesimal cluster, and simultaneously a quantity (the cardinality of a
   356	counted collection). The paper traces this dual aspect through Mill's
   357	empiricism, Husserl's phenomenology of arithmetic, Frege's critique of
   358	psychologism in \emph{Grundlagen der Arithmetik}~\cite{frege1884} and
   359	\emph{Sinn und Bedeutung}~\cite{frege1892}, and Benacerraf's identification
   360	problem~\cite{benacerraf1965}.
   361	
   362	The principal lesson of Paper~I is the syntax/semantics distinction: numerals
   363	are syntactic objects (symbols, words over an alphabet), while numbers are
   364	the semantic invariants that all adequate numeral systems share. The paper
   365	provides a Haskell artifact parsing four numeral systems (Hindu--Arabic,
   366	Roman, tally, Babylonian sexagesimal) into a single structural normal form.
   367	
   368	The naive level is shown to be simultaneously \emph{insufficient} (because
   369	of symbol/object confusion, multiplicity of equally adequate
   370	representations, and a foundational underdetermination that already
   371	foreshadows the structuralist response) and \emph{indispensable} (because
   372	embodied counting and culturally-transmitted numerals anchor mathematical
   373	content in human cognition). The paper closes by motivating each of the
   374	five formal levels developed in subsequent papers.
   375	
   376	\subsection{Paper II: Set-theoretic --- numbers as von Neumann ordinals}
   377	\label{sec:row-ii}
   378	
   379	Paper~II~\cite{paper-ii} works in Zermelo--Fraenkel set theory with Choice
   380	(ZFC). It develops the von Neumann encoding $0 = \emptyset$,
   381	$n + 1 = n \cup \{n\}$, in which $58 = \{0, 1, \ldots, 57\}$, and contrasts
   382	it with Zermelo's encoding $0 = \emptyset$, $n + 1 = \{n\}$. Both yield
   383	structures isomorphic to $(\N, 0, \suc)$ as Peano models, yet they differ
   384	on internal set-theoretic questions such as whether $2 \in 3$.
   385	
   386	The paper proves Benacerraf's argument formally:
   387	
   388	\begin{theorem}[Benacerraf, formalised in Paper~II]
   389	\label{thm:benacerraf}
   390	There exist two ZFC-definable structures $(N_v, 0_v, \suc_v)$ and
   391	$(N_z, 0_z, \suc_z)$ which both satisfy the second-order Peano axioms and
   392	are isomorphic as Peano structures, but which differ on a sentence of
   393	ZFC's first-order language (e.g.\ ``$\exists x \in 2.\, x = 1$'').
   394	Therefore, no choice of ZFC encoding can claim to be the unique correct
   395	$\N$.
   396	\end{theorem}
   397	
   398	The paper develops addition, multiplication, and order recursively on the
   399	von Neumann ordinals, verifies the Peano axioms, and proves a representation
   400	theorem stating that any successor structure obtained from a class function
   401	$S$ that is injective, has a base point not in its image, and admits
   402	transfinite iteration generates a model of Peano arithmetic isomorphic to
   403	the von Neumann naturals. It closes with a structuralist re-reading: the
   404	set-theoretic perspective \emph{does} present numbers, but only as
   405	encodings; the structural content these encodings share is what we call
   406	\emph{the number itself}.
   407	
   408	\subsection{Paper III: Universal property --- numbers as initial successor structures}
   409	\label{sec:row-iii}
   410	
   411	Paper~III~\cite{paper-iii} introduces the natural numbers object (NNO).
   412	
   413	\begin{definition}[NNO, Paper~III]
   414	\label{def:nno}
   415	A \emph{natural numbers object} in a category $\mathcal{C}$ with terminal
   416	object $\mathbf{1}$ is a triple $(N, 0\colon \mathbf{1} \to N,
   417	\suc\colon N \to N)$ that is the initial $(0, \suc)$-algebra. Equivalently,
   418	$(N, [0, \suc])$ is initial among algebras for the endofunctor
   419	$F X = \mathbf{1} + X$ (Lambek).
   420	\end{definition}
   421	
   422	\begin{theorem}[Universal property, Paper~III, Theorem~3.2]
   423	\label{thm:nno-up}
   424	Let $(N, 0, \suc)$ be an NNO in $\mathcal{C}$. For every pointed dynamical
   425	system $(X, x_0, f)$ in $\mathcal{C}$, there exists a unique morphism
   426	$h\colon N \to X$ such that
   427	\[
   428	h \circ 0 = x_0 \quad \text{and} \quad h \circ \suc = f \circ h.
   429	\]
   430	\end{theorem}
   431	
   432	The unique map $h$ \emph{is} the primitive recursion combinator
   433	$\mathrm{rec}(x_0, f)$. The integer $58$ is, in any NNO,
   434	$\suc^{58}(0)$, and any two NNOs are canonically isomorphic via the unique
   435	maps in both directions, so $58$ is well-defined up to that canonical
   436	isomorphism.
   437	
   438	Paper~III also proves equivalence with second-order Peano axioms
   439	(P1--P5), discusses non-standard models of first-order PA (which the
   440	universal-property characterisation excludes), develops universal-property
   441	descriptions of $\Z$, $\Q$, $\R$, $\pi$, $e$, and presents the coalgebraic
   442	dual (final coalgebras, streams as $\nu X.\, D \times X$, codata,
   443	bisimulation as the corresponding induction principle).
   444	
   445	The paper closes by recasting the NNO Yonedically: a universal property is
   446	a representation of a functor, and the NNO represents the constant singleton
   447	functor on $\PtEndo$. This bridges to Paper~IV.
   448	
   449	\subsection{Paper IV: Yoneda --- numbers as representable functors}
   450	\label{sec:row-iv}
   451	
   452	Paper~IV~\cite{paper-iv} promotes the relational viewpoint to its
   453	categorical limit.
   454	
   455	\begin{theorem}[Yoneda lemma, Paper~IV, Theorem~3.1]
   456	\label{thm:yoneda}
   457	For any locally small category $\mathcal{C}$, object $X \in \mathcal{C}$,
   458	and presheaf $F\colon \mathcal{C}\op \to \Set$, the map
   459	\[
   460	\Phi_{X,F}\colon \Nat(\Hom_{\mathcal{C}}(-, X), F) \to F(X), \qquad
   461	\alpha \mapsto \alpha_X(\id_X)
   462	\]
   463	is a bijection, natural in both $X$ and $F$.
   464	\end{theorem}
   465	
   466	\begin{corollary}[Fully faithful Yoneda embedding]
   467	The functor $y\colon \mathcal{C} \to [\mathcal{C}\op, \Set]$,
   468	$X \mapsto \Hom(-, X)$, is fully faithful. Hence
   469	$X \iso Y \iff h_X \iso h_Y$.
   470	\end{corollary}
   471	
   472	In the category $\PtEndo$ of pointed dynamical systems, the natural number
   473	$58$ is identified with the functor that assigns to every
   474	$(X, x_0, f)$ the value $f^{58}(x_0)$. The structuralist's slogan
   475	``numbers are positions in a structure'' is now a theorem.
   476	
   477	Paper~IV also proves the density theorem (every presheaf is a colimit of
   478	representables), surveys applications to groups (regular representations),
   479	spaces (functor of points), and schemes (Grothendieck's program), and
   480	develops enriched, $2$-categorical, and $\infty$-categorical Yoneda
   481	(culminating in Lurie's $\infty$-Yoneda lemma~\cite{lurie}). It closes by
   482	arguing that under univalence, the implication
   483	$h_X \iso h_Y \Rightarrow X = Y$ is internalised as a path in the universe,
   484	preparing Paper~V.
   485	
   486	\subsection{Paper V: HoTT --- numbers as inductive types up to path equivalence}
   487	\label{sec:row-v}
   488	
   489	Paper~V~\cite{paper-v} is a self-contained development of Homotopy Type
   490	Theory. The natural numbers are the inductive type
   491	\[
   492	\N \,:\!\!=\, \mathsf{data}\, \N : \U \;|\; \zero : \N \;|\; \suc : \N \to \N,
   493	\]
   494	and $58$ is the canonical term $\suc^{58}\,\zero$.
   495	
   496	The novelty of HoTT is the identity type $a =_A b$, which is not a mere
   497	proposition but a structured object carrying the homotopical content of a
   498	\emph{path space}. The paper develops path induction, transport, coherence,
   499	and the homotopy levels, and states Voevodsky's univalence axiom:
   500	
   501	\begin{theorem}[Univalence axiom, Paper~V, Theorem~4.2]
   502	\label{thm:univalence}
   503	For all types $A, B : \U$, the canonical map
   504	$\idtoeqv\colon (A =_\U B) \to (A \eqv B)$ is itself an equivalence. The
   505	inverse map is denoted
   506	\[
   507	\ua\colon (A \eqv B) \to (A =_\U B).
   508	\]
   509	\end{theorem}
   510	
   511	The paper proves a contractibility theorem for the type of NNOs in HoTT:
   512	
   513	\begin{theorem}[Contractibility of NNO, Paper~V, Theorem~4.4]
   514	\label{thm:nno-contr}
   515	The type
   516	\[
   517	\NNO := \sum_{X : \U}\;\sum_{x_0 : X}\;\sum_{s : X \to X}\;
   518	\mathsf{isInitial}(X, x_0, s)
   519	\]
   520	is contractible. The centre of contraction is $(\N, \zero, \suc, \star)$,
   521	and every other quadruple is connected to it by a unique path.
   522	\end{theorem}
   523	
   524	This is the formal expression of the slogan ``$58$ is canonical across all
   525	NNOs.'' Paper~V also develops higher inductive types (interval, circle,
   526	spheres, suspensions, pushouts, propositional truncation, Cauchy real
   527	numbers as a higher inductive--inductive type), the cubical realisation of
   528	HoTT~\cite{CCHM,CubicalAgda} in which univalence is provable rather than
   529	axiomatic, two-level type theory~\cite{2LTT}, modal HoTT, and directed
   530	HoTT~\cite{RiehlShulman}.
   531	
   532	\subsection{Paper VI: Categorical / structural --- numbers as invariants}
   533	\label{sec:row-vi}
   534	
   535	Paper~VI~\cite{paper-vi} presents the structural answer to ``what is a
   536	number?''. Numerals are invariants under all structure-preserving
   537	morphisms between models of arithmetic. The paper surveys mathematical
   538	structuralism in the philosophical
   539	tradition~\cite{Resnik1997,Shapiro1997,Hellman1989,Awodey1996}, presents
   540	its categorical formalisation through Lawvere's ETCS~\cite{Lawvere1964}
   541	and the functorial semantics of algebraic theories~\cite{Lawvere1963},
   542	and proves an isomorphism-invariance theorem for first-order properties
   543	of finitely-presented theories.
   544	
   545	\begin{theorem}[Structure identity principle, Paper~VI, Theorem~10.3]
   546	\label{thm:sip}
   547	Let $\mathcal{S}$ be a notion of structure given by a $\Sigma$-type
   548	$\sum_{X : \U} F(X)$ for $F$ a structure of finite signature. In HoTT,
   549	identification of structures is canonically equivalent to
   550	structure-preserving equivalence of carriers:
   551	\[
   552	\bigl((X, s) =_{\sum_X F(X)} (X', s')\bigr) \;\eqv\;
   553	\bigl(\sum_{f : X \eqv X'}\, f \text{ preserves } s, s'\bigr).
   554	\]
   555	\end{theorem}
   556	
   557	\begin{theorem}[Equivalence-invariance, Paper~VI, Theorem~10.4]
   558	\label{thm:eq-inv}
   559	In HoTT, every property $P : \mathcal{S} \to \U$ of structures of a given
   560	kind is automatically invariant under structure-preserving equivalence:
   561	$(X, s) \eqv (X', s')$ implies $P(X, s) \eqv P(X', s')$.
   562	\end{theorem}
   563	
   564	The paper exhibits two non-equal but isomorphic set-theoretic models of a
   565	small algebraic theory of pointed unary structures and verifies, formally
   566	and by Haskell code, that all numerical answers (cardinalities of
   567	definable subsets, values of definable functions) coincide. It connects
   568	categorification ($58$-element groupoid in $\Grpd$ that decategorifies to
   569	$58$ in $\Set$ via $\pi_0$) and Euler-characteristic / $K$-theoretic
   570	decategorification to the same invariance principle.
   571	
   572	\section{The Five Transit Theorems}
   573	\label{sec:transit}
   574	
   575	Each of the five steps from one row to the next has formal content. We
   576	collect those steps as theorems and prove them, where the proofs are not
   577	already inside the topical papers.
   578	
   579	\subsection{Naive to set-theoretic}
   580	\label{sec:transit-i}
   581	
   582	\begin{theorem}[Existence of a definite encoding]
   583	\label{thm:transit-i}
   584	There exists a class function $V : \N \to V_\omega$ in ZFC, defined by
   585	$V(0) = \emptyset$, $V(n+1) = V(n) \cup \{V(n)\}$, such that every numeral
   586	in any of the four numeral systems of Paper~I (Hindu--Arabic, Roman, tally,
   587	Babylonian sexagesimal) determines, via parsing, a unique element of the
   588	image of $V$.
   589	\end{theorem}
   590	
   591	\begin{proof}
   592	The recursion is justified by Replacement and Foundation in ZFC; see
   593	Paper~II, Theorem~3.4. The parsers are constructed in Paper~I, \S8.
   594	\end{proof}
   595	
   596	\Cref{thm:transit-i} resolves the naive symbol/object confusion: there is
   597	a definite mathematical object the numeral refers to. But it does not
   598	resolve which one: that is Benacerraf's problem (\cref{thm:benacerraf}).
   599	
   600	\subsection{Set-theoretic to universal property}
   601	\label{sec:transit-ii}
   602	
   603	\begin{theorem}[Encoding $\Rightarrow$ NNO]
   604	\label{thm:transit-ii}
   605	The von Neumann encoding $V$ exhibits $(\N_v, \emptyset, n \mapsto n \cup \{n\})$
   606	as a natural numbers object in $\Set$. The Zermelo encoding $Z$ exhibits
   607	$(\N_z, \emptyset, n \mapsto \{n\})$ as a natural numbers object in $\Set$.
   608	The unique map $h\colon \N_v \to \N_z$ guaranteed by the universal property
   609	of $\N_v$ is the bijection sending $V(n)$ to $Z(n)$, and is canonical.
   610	\end{theorem}
   611	
   612	\begin{proof}
   613	That both structures satisfy the second-order Peano axioms is Paper~II,
   614	Theorems~3.5 and~4.2. By Paper~III, Theorem~7.1, second-order Peano is
   615	equivalent to NNO. Initiality (and hence the canonical bijection) follows.
   616	\end{proof}
   617	
   618	\Cref{thm:transit-ii} resolves Benacerraf: the von Neumann and Zermelo
   619	encodings do not name the same set, but they name the same NNO up to a
   620	unique iso. The universal property is the encoding-independent shadow.
   621	
   622	\subsection{Universal property to Yoneda}
   623	\label{sec:transit-iii}
   624	
   625	\begin{theorem}[NNO as a representation]
   626	\label{thm:transit-iii}
   627	Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category with terminal object. The forgetful
   628	functor $U\colon \PtEndo(\mathcal{C}) \to \mathcal{C}$ has a left adjoint
   629	$F$ if and only if $\mathcal{C}$ admits an NNO. In that case
   630	$N = F(\mathbf{0})$ where $\mathbf{0}$ is the initial object of
   631	$\mathcal{C}$ (or, equivalently, $N$ is the value of the free pointed
   632	endo-system on the empty set), and the universal property of the NNO is
   633	exactly the unit of the adjunction.
   634	\end{theorem}
   635	
   636	\begin{proof}
   637	We connect the adjunction to Yoneda in two steps.
   638	
   639	\emph{Step 1: adjunction $\Rightarrow$ universal property.} Suppose $F$
   640	is left adjoint to $U$. The unit $\eta\colon \id_\mathcal{C} \to U F$ at the
   641	initial object $\mathbf{0} \in \mathcal{C}$ is the universal map
   642	$\eta_\mathbf{0}\colon \mathbf{0} \to U F (\mathbf{0})$. By the
   643	adjunction's hom-set bijection
   644	$\Hom_{\PtEndo}(F(\mathbf{0}), (X, x_0, f)) \iso \Hom_\mathcal{C}(\mathbf{0}, U(X, x_0, f))$,
   645	the right-hand side is a singleton (initiality of $\mathbf{0}$), so the
   646	left-hand side is too: there is a \emph{unique} morphism
   647	$F(\mathbf{0}) \to (X, x_0, f)$ for every pointed endo-system. This is
   648	precisely the universal property of the NNO (\cref{thm:nno-up}) with
   649	$N := F(\mathbf{0})$. Conversely, an NNO supplies the action of $F$ on
   650	objects and the unit, and naturality of the bijection is forced by the
   651	universal property.
   652	
   653	\emph{Step 2: universal property $\Rightarrow$ Yoneda representation.}
   654	Reading the previous bijection as an isomorphism of presheaves on
   655	$\PtEndo$,
   656	\[
   657	\Hom_{\PtEndo}(N, -) \;\iso\; \Delta_{\mathbf{1}},
   658	\]
   659	where $\Delta_{\mathbf{1}}$ is the constant singleton presheaf, exhibits
   660	$N$ as a representing object for $\Delta_{\mathbf{1}}$. The Yoneda
   661	embedding sends $N$ to the representable $h_N \in [\PtEndo\op, \Set]$,
   662	which equals (up to natural iso) the constant singleton presheaf. Thus
   663	the universal property is exactly the assertion that $h_N \iso \Delta_{\mathbf{1}}$,
   664	which is the Yoneda formulation. See Paper~III, Proposition~9.2 for the
   665	full computation.
   666	\end{proof}
   667	
   668	\subsection{Yoneda to HoTT}
   669	\label{sec:transit-iv}
   670	
   671	\begin{theorem}[Yoneda + univalence $\Rightarrow$ identity]
   672	\label{thm:transit-iv}
   673	Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a univalent category in HoTT (in the sense of
   674	\cite[Definition~9.1.6]{HoTTBook}: a category in which the canonical map
   675	$(A = B) \to (A \iso B)$ is an equivalence). Then for $X, Y \in \mathcal{C}$
   676	the chain
   677	\[
   678	(X = Y) \;\eqv\; (X \iso Y) \;\eqv\; (h_X \iso h_Y) \;\eqv\; (h_X = h_Y)
   679	\]
   680	of equivalences holds, with the first being the univalence-of-$\mathcal{C}$
   681	condition, the second being the Yoneda corollary, and the third being
   682	univalence of the functor category $[\mathcal{C}\op, \U]$.
   683	\end{theorem}
   684	
   685	\begin{proof}
   686	The first equivalence is by definition of a univalent category. The second
   687	is the Yoneda corollary (Paper~IV, Corollary~3.4). The third is by
   688	function-extensionality and univalence applied componentwise; see
   689	\cite[Theorem~9.2.5]{HoTTBook}. Composing the three gives an equivalence
   690	$(X = Y) \eqv (h_X = h_Y)$, which is the desired internal identification.
   691	\end{proof}
   692	
   693	\Cref{thm:transit-iv} is the technical heart of the strong univalent
   694	correspondence: Yoneda's ``iff'' becomes a four-way chain of equivalences,
   695	each two adjacent terms identified internally, so that the entire chain
   696	collapses to one type up to equivalence.
   697	
   698	\subsection{HoTT to categorical / structural}
   699	\label{sec:transit-vi}
   700	
   701	\begin{theorem}[Univalence $\Rightarrow$ structural]
   702	\label{thm:transit-vi}
   703	In HoTT, every type-theoretic property $P$ of an algebraic structure is
   704	automatically structural in the sense of Paper~VI: if
   705	$(X, s) \eqv (X', s')$ as structures, then $P(X, s) \eqv P(X', s')$. In
   706	particular, the natural number $58$, defined as $\suc^{58}\,\zero$ in any
   707	NNO, agrees with $58$ in any equivalent NNO presentation.
   708	\end{theorem}
   709	
   710	\begin{proof}
   711	This is the structure identity principle (\cref{thm:sip}, Paper~VI,
   712	Theorem~10.3) combined with path-action of $P$. The application to $58$
   713	is \cite[Corollary~5.4]{paper-v} (\cref{thm:nno-contr}).
   714	\end{proof}
   715	
   716	\Cref{thm:transit-vi} is the converse direction of the previous transit:
   717	the structural perspective of Paper~VI is no longer a methodological
   718	discipline (``write only iso-invariant definitions'') but a theorem of the
   719	foundations (``every definition you can write \emph{is} iso-invariant'').
   720	Univalence is the principle that promotes the meta-condition to an
   721	internal one. We summarise the four-layer convergence in
   722	\cref{tab:four-layers}, reproduced from Paper~VI.
   723	
   724	\begin{table}[ht]
   725	\centering
   726	\begin{tabular}{lll}
   727	\toprule
   728	\textbf{Layer (Paper)} & \textbf{Statement} & \textbf{Status} \\
   729	\midrule
   730	Categorical / structural (VI) & Structural properties are iso-invariant
   731	& Meta-theorem \\
   732	Universal property (III) & Iso-class is canonical & Theorem (NNO uniqueness) \\
   733	Yoneda (IV) & Object known by relations & Theorem (Yoneda) \\
   734	HoTT + univalence (V) & Iso-invariance is automatic & Internal (SIP) \\
   735	\bottomrule
   736	\end{tabular}
   737	\caption{Four layers of one principle. Adapted from Paper~VI,
   738	Table~10.1.}
   739	\label{tab:four-layers}
   740	\end{table}
   741	
   742	\section{Unified Framework: One \texorpdfstring{$\infty$}{Infinity}-Groupoid, Four Windows}
   743	\label{sec:framework}
   744	
   745	We now build the mathematical framework in which the four right-most rows
   746	of \cref{tab:six-rows} become four windows on a single object.
   747	
   748	\subsection{Setup: a univalent universe}
   749	\label{sec:setup-univ}
   750	
   751	Let $\U$ be a univalent universe of types in HoTT. We work informally in
   752	HoTT throughout; the reader who prefers a categorical semantics may
   753	interpret all our types as objects of an $(\infty,1)$-topos, e.g.\ the
   754	$\infty$-topos of $\infty$-groupoids, or any
   755	Grothendieck--Rezk--Lurie--Joyal $\infty$-topos~\cite{lurie,ShulmanInftyTopos}.
   756	
   757	\begin{definition}[The four-perspective functors]
   758	\label{def:four-functors}
   759	Fix a notion of structure given by a $\Sigma$-type
   760	\[
   761	\mathcal{S} \;:=\; \sum_{X : \U} F(X)
   762	\]
   763	for some structure-of-finite-signature predicate $F : \U \to \U$ (e.g.\
   764	pointed unary structures, the signature of an NNO). Write a typical
   765	structure as a pair $\mathbf{X} = (X, s)$ where $X : \U$ is the carrier
   766	and $s : F(X)$ is the structure data. Let $\mathcal{C}_\mathcal{S}$
   767	denote the category whose objects are inhabitants of $\mathcal{S}$ and
   768	whose morphisms are structure-preserving maps. Define four functors:
   769	\begin{itemize}
   770	\item $\mathsf{UP}\colon \mathcal{S} \to \mathsf{Prop}_\U$ sending
   771	$\mathbf{X}$ to the mere proposition $\mathsf{isInitial}(\mathbf{X})$ of
   772	being initial in $\mathcal{C}_\mathcal{S}$;
   773	\item $\mathsf{Y}\colon \mathcal{S} \to [\mathcal{C}_\mathcal{S}\op, \U]$
   774	sending $\mathbf{X}$ to the presheaf
   775	$h_{\mathbf{X}} = \Hom_{\mathcal{C}_\mathcal{S}}(-, \mathbf{X})$
   776	(the Yoneda embedding restricted to $\mathcal{C}_\mathcal{S}$);
   777	\item $\mathsf{H}\colon \mathcal{S} \to \U$ sending $\mathbf{X} = (X, s)$
   778	to its carrier $X$ with identity types unfolded to path spaces;
   779	\item $\mathsf{S}\colon \mathcal{S} \to \mathcal{S}/\eqv$ sending
   780	$\mathbf{X}$ to its isomorphism class of $\mathcal{S}$-structures.
   781	\end{itemize}
   782	The functors $\mathsf{UP}, \mathsf{Y}, \mathsf{H}, \mathsf{S}$ are the
   783	four windows on a fixed $\mathcal{S}$-structure.
   784	\end{definition}
   785	
   786	\begin{theorem}[Identity of perspectives]
   787	\label{thm:identity-of-perspectives}
   788	For $\mathbf{X}, \mathbf{Y} : \mathcal{S}$, the four statements
   789	\begin{enumerate}
   790	\item[(UP)] $\mathsf{UP}(\mathbf{X}) \times \mathsf{UP}(\mathbf{Y})$
   791	together with the resulting unique iso $\mathbf{X} \iso \mathbf{Y}$ in
   792	$\mathcal{C}_\mathcal{S}$;
   793	\item[(Y)] $\mathsf{Y}(\mathbf{X}) \iso \mathsf{Y}(\mathbf{Y})$ in
   794	$[\mathcal{C}_\mathcal{S}\op, \U]$;
   795	\item[(H)] a path
   796	$p\colon \mathsf{H}(\mathbf{X}) =_\U \mathsf{H}(\mathbf{Y})$ together
   797	with a transport-coherence witness for the structure data;
   798	\item[(S)] $\mathsf{S}(\mathbf{X}) = \mathsf{S}(\mathbf{Y})$ as elements
   799	of the quotient $\mathcal{S}/\eqv$;
   800	\end{enumerate}
   801	are pairwise equivalent. Therefore, under the univalence axiom and SIP,
   802	they all reduce to the type
   803	$\mathbf{X} =_\mathcal{S} \mathbf{Y}$, which is itself an
   804	$\infty$-groupoid (the path space).
   805	\end{theorem}
   806	
   807	\begin{proof}
   808	\textbf{(UP)~$\Rightarrow$~(Y).} If $\mathbf{X}$ and $\mathbf{Y}$ are
   809	both initial in $\mathcal{C}_\mathcal{S}$, the unique morphisms in both
   810	directions exhibit $\mathbf{X} \iso \mathbf{Y}$. By full faithfulness of
   811	Yoneda, $h_{\mathbf{X}} \iso h_{\mathbf{Y}}$.
   812	
   813	\textbf{(Y)~$\Rightarrow$~(H).} By \cref{thm:transit-iv}, applied to the
   814	univalent category $\mathcal{C}_\mathcal{S}$, the isomorphism
   815	$h_{\mathbf{X}} \iso h_{\mathbf{Y}}$ is equivalent to a path
   816	$h_{\mathbf{X}} = h_{\mathbf{Y}}$, which by univalence of the presheaf
   817	category gives an iso of carriers and hence (after structure transport)
   818	the path $p$ together with its coherence witness.
   819	
   820	\textbf{(H)~$\Rightarrow$~(S).} We unpack this step. The hypothesis is a
   821	path $p\colon \mathsf{H}(\mathbf{X}) =_\U \mathsf{H}(\mathbf{Y})$
   822	between carriers, together with a transport-coherence witness
   823	$q\colon \transport^F(p)(s_X) =_{F(\mathsf{H}(\mathbf{Y}))} s_Y$
   824	identifying the structure data after transport. By the construction of
   825	paths in $\Sigma$-types
   826	\cite[Theorem~2.7.2]{HoTTBook}, the pair $(p, q)$ is exactly an
   827	inhabitant of the type $\mathbf{X} =_\mathcal{S} \mathbf{Y}$ where the
   828	right-hand side is a path in the $\Sigma$-type
   829	$\sum_{X : \U} F(X)$ that defines $\mathcal{S}$. SIP
   830	(\cref{thm:sip}) then asserts that this $\Sigma$-path is itself
   831	canonically equivalent to a structure-preserving equivalence
   832	$\sum_{f : X \eqv X'}\, f \text{ preserves } s, s'$. Quotienting by
   833	$\eqv$ yields the equality
   834	$\mathsf{S}(\mathbf{X}) = \mathsf{S}(\mathbf{Y})$ in
   835	$\mathcal{S}/\eqv$.
   836	
   837	\textbf{(S)~$\Rightarrow$~(UP).} If
   838	$\mathsf{S}(\mathbf{X}) = \mathsf{S}(\mathbf{Y})$, the representatives are
   839	isomorphic, so both are initial or neither is. The remaining content of
   840	(UP) (the unique morphisms) follows from initiality of either via SIP.
   841	
   842	The cycle closes; pairwise equivalence follows. The fact that the common
   843	type is an $\infty$-groupoid is built into HoTT: identity types are types,
   844	their identity types are types, and so on.
   845	\end{proof}
   846	
   847	\Cref{thm:identity-of-perspectives} is the technical formulation of
   848	\cref{prin:strong}. The four statements (UP), (Y), (H), (S) are not just
   849	analogous; they all live as inhabitants of the same path-type
   850	$\mathbf{X} =_\mathcal{S} \mathbf{Y}$ in the type of structures.
   851	
   852	\subsection{The unifying picture}
   853	
   854	\Cref{fig:four-views} shows the unified picture: a single $\infty$-groupoid
   855	viewed through four functors, each producing one of the four columns of
   856	the computational tetrad.
   857	
   858	\begin{figure}[ht]
   859	\centering
   860	\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2.0cm and 2.5cm]
   861	\node (X) [draw, circle, minimum size=2cm, thick] {$X \in \U$};
   862	\node (UP) [above left=of X] {$(\mathsf{UP})$ initial in $\mathcal{S}$};
   863	\node (Y) [above right=of X] {$(\mathsf{Y})$ representable functor};
   864	\node (H) [below left=of X] {$(\mathsf{H})$ canonical term in $\U$};
   865	\node (S) [below right=of X] {$(\mathsf{S})$ structural invariant};
   866	\draw[-{Stealth[length=3mm]}] (X) -- (UP);
   867	\draw[-{Stealth[length=3mm]}] (X) -- (Y);
   868	\draw[-{Stealth[length=3mm]}] (X) -- (H);
   869	\draw[-{Stealth[length=3mm]}] (X) -- (S);
   870	\draw[<->, dashed] (UP) -- (Y) node[midway, above] {$\eqv$};
   871	\draw[<->, dashed] (Y) -- (S) node[midway, right] {$\eqv$};
   872	\draw[<->, dashed] (S) -- (H) node[midway, below] {$\eqv$};
   873	\draw[<->, dashed] (H) -- (UP) node[midway, left] {$\eqv$};
   874	\end{tikzpicture}
   875	\caption{One $\infty$-groupoid, four windows. The four functors of
   876	\cref{def:four-functors} produce the four characterisations of $X$. Under
   877	univalence and SIP, all four characterisations are pairwise equivalent
   878	(\cref{thm:identity-of-perspectives}).}
   879	\label{fig:four-views}
   880	\end{figure}
   881	
   882	\subsection{Stratification by homotopy level}
   883	
   884	The $\infty$-groupoid view stratifies. For the natural number type $\N$,
   885	which is a $0$-type (a set, in the HoTT Book's $n$-type indexing where
   886	contractible types are $(-2)$-types) by~\cite[Theorem~7.1.6]{HoTTBook}, the
   887	$\infty$-groupoid of NNOs is in fact a contractible $\infty$-groupoid, by
   888	\cref{thm:nno-contr}. So the path space between any two NNO presentations
   889	is itself contractible: the canonical iso between $\N_v$ and $\N_z$ is
   890	not just unique up to ambient choices but \emph{essentially uniquely
   891	unique}, with all higher coherences automatic. This is what
   892	\cref{thm:nno-contr} achieves that mere Peano-equivalence does not.
   893	
   894	For $\R$, defined as a higher inductive--inductive type via Cauchy
   895	completion~\cite{Booij,HoTTBook}, the situation is more delicate: $\R$ is
   896	a set ($0$-type) under the propositional truncation conditions of the
   897	HIIT, but the construction of $\R$ from $\Q$ involves higher path
   898	constructors. The transcendentals $\pi$ and $e$ then appear as definite
   899	(canonical-up-to-path) inhabitants of $\R$ via universal-property
   900	characterisations
   901	($\sin(\pi) = 0$, $f' = f$ and $f(0) = 1$, etc.); see \cref{sec:applications}.
   902	
   903	\section{The Univalent Correspondence: Statement and Consequences}
   904	\label{sec:correspondence}
   905	
   906	We now state the principle systematically.
   907	
   908	\begin{principle}[The univalent correspondence, formal version]
   909	\label{prin:formal}
   910	Let $\mathcal{S}$ be a notion of structure given by an essentially
   911	algebraic theory in HoTT. Let $X, Y$ be $\mathcal{S}$-structures in a
   912	univalent universe $\U$. Then the following are pairwise equivalent in
   913	$\U$:
   914	\begin{itemize}
   915	\item[\textsc{(I)}] $X$ and $Y$ both have the same universal property
   916	(both initial, both terminal, both representing the same functor, etc.).
   917	\item[\textsc{(II)}] The Yoneda embeddings $h_X$ and $h_Y$ are
   918	isomorphic as presheaves.
   919	\item[\textsc{(III)}] $\mathsf{H}(X) =_\U \mathsf{H}(Y)$ as types
   920	(identity in the universe).
   921	\item[\textsc{(IV)}] $X$ and $Y$ are equal as elements of the type of
   922	$\mathcal{S}$-structures.
   923	\end{itemize}
   924	The equivalences \textsc{(I)}~$\Leftrightarrow$~\textsc{(II)} and
   925	\textsc{(II)}~$\Leftrightarrow$~\textsc{(III)} are theorems; the
   926	equivalence \textsc{(III)}~$\Leftrightarrow$~\textsc{(IV)} requires the
   927	structure identity principle (a theorem in HoTT, established for
   928	finite-signature structures in~\cite{HoTTBook,Escardo2019}). The
   929	equivalence \textsc{(I)}~$\Leftrightarrow$~\textsc{(IV)} requires
   930	univalence.
   931	\end{principle}
   932	
   933	\subsection{The fixed-point reading}
   934	
   935	\Cref{prin:formal} can be read as a fixed-point statement. The four
   936	columns of the computational tetrad (\cref{tab:tetrad}) describe four
   937	languages for talking about objects: logic, type theory, category
   938	theory, homotopy theory. Univalence is the assertion that, for the
   939	universe of types, the four languages have a common semantic
   940	fixed point: a single $\infty$-groupoid that satisfies all four
   941	descriptions simultaneously, with the four descriptions identified along
   942	the chain of equivalences just listed.
   943	
   944	\begin{remark}[Curry--Howard--Lambek--Voevodsky]
   945	The Curry--Howard correspondence~\cite{Wadler2015} identifies columns~1
   946	and~2 (logic with type theory). The Curry--Howard--Lambek
   947	correspondence~\cite{Lambek1972,maclane} adds column~3 (category theory).
   948	Voevodsky's univalent foundations~\cite{Voevodsky,HoTTBook} adds
   949	column~4 (homotopy theory) by interpreting types as $\infty$-groupoids
   950	and asserting univalence. The univalent correspondence is the strong
   951	form of the four-way Curry--Howard--Lambek--Voevodsky correspondence.
   952	\end{remark}
   953	
   954	\subsection{Application to the natural numbers}
   955	
   956	\begin{corollary}[The natural numbers are univalent]
   957	\label{cor:N-univalent}
   958	Let $\NNO$ be the type of NNO structures in $\U$. The following are all
   959	the same data, up to canonical equivalence:
   960	\begin{itemize}
   961	\item the universal-property data $(N, 0, \suc, \mathsf{isInitial})$;
   962	\item the representable presheaf $h_N \in [\NNO\op, \U]$;
   963	\item the canonical inhabitant of the contractible type $\NNO$;
   964	\item the iso-class $[(N, 0, \suc)]$ in $\NNO/\eqv$.
   965	\end{itemize}
   966	The integer $58$, defined as $\suc^{58}\,\zero$, is invariant under all
   967	four identifications.
   968	\end{corollary}
   969	
   970	\begin{proof}
   971	Combine \cref{thm:nno-contr,thm:identity-of-perspectives,thm:transit-vi}.
   972	\end{proof}
   973	
   974	\subsection{Why this resolves the original question}
   975	
   976	The original question of the series, ``what is $58$?'', has now four
   977	equivalent answers, each made precise by one of Papers~III through~VI:
   978	\begin{itemize}
   979	\item \emph{(III)} $58$ is the unique element such that, for every pointed
   980	endo-system $(X, x_0, f)$ in any category with terminal object, the unique
   981	NNO morphism $h\colon \N \to X$ sends $58$ to $f^{58}(x_0)$.
   982	\item \emph{(IV)} $58$ is the natural number whose representable functor
   983	$\Hom(-, 58)$, under the Yoneda embedding into the presheaf topos, exhibits
   984	all probes onto $58$ from below.
   985	\item \emph{(V)} $58$ is the canonical term $\suc^{58}\,\zero : \N$,
   986	identified with $\suc^{58}\,\zero$ in any equivalent NNO presentation by
   987	transport along the unique path in the contractible type $\NNO$.
   988	\item \emph{(VI)} $58$ is the value of any (every) definable arithmetic
   989	quantity that, on the standard model of arithmetic, evaluates to $58$;
   990	this value is invariant under all model isomorphisms by SIP.
   991	\end{itemize}
   992	The univalent correspondence asserts that these four answers are not just
   993	\emph{about} the same object: they are \emph{the same data}, internally,
   994	in HoTT.
   995	
   996	\section{Hierarchical Composition: How Each Level Builds on the Previous}
   997	\label{sec:diagrams}
   998	
   999	The univalent correspondence is not just a parallel array of four
  1000	descriptions: it is a hierarchical composition in which each level uses
  1001	the data of the previous one. We make the dependencies explicit.
  1002	
  1003	\subsection{Composition diagram}
  1004	
  1005	\Cref{fig:composition} shows the dependencies between the six rows.
  1006	
  1007	\begin{figure}[ht]
  1008	\centering
  1009	\begin{tikzcd}[column sep=2.4em, row sep=large]
  1010	\text{(I) Naive}
  1011	  \arrow[r, "{\text{T1}}", "{\text{definite encoding}}"']
  1012	& \text{(II) Set-theoretic}
  1013	  \arrow[r, "{\text{T2}}", "{\text{Benacerraf}\,\Rightarrow\,\text{NNO}}"']
  1014	& \text{(III) Universal property}
  1015	  \arrow[r, "{\text{T3}}", "{\text{NNO is rep.\ functor}}"']
  1016	& \text{(IV) Yoneda}
  1017	  \arrow[r, "{\text{T4}}", "{\text{univalence}}"']
  1018	& \text{(V) HoTT}
  1019	  \arrow[r, "{\text{T5}}", "{\text{SIP}}"']
  1020	& \text{(VI) Structural}
  1021	\end{tikzcd}
  1022	\caption{Hierarchical composition: each transit theorem
  1023	T$k$ of \cref{sec:transit} carries level $k$ to level $k+1$ by
  1024	resolving the residual question of the previous level. T1 supplies a
  1025	definite encoding (resolving the symbol/object confusion). T2 abstracts
  1026	away from the Benacerraf-non-canonical encoding. T3 globalises the
  1027	universal property by exhibiting the NNO as a representable functor. T4
  1028	internalises Yoneda's ``iff'' as a path in the universe via univalence.
  1029	T5 (\cref{thm:transit-vi}) promotes the iso-invariance discipline to an
  1030	internal theorem via SIP.}
  1031	\label{fig:composition}
  1032	\end{figure}
  1033	
  1034	\subsection{Composition is not optional}
  1035	
  1036	A natural objection: if all four formal levels (III--VI) are equivalent
  1037	under univalence, why bother with all four? Why not just use HoTT?
  1038	
  1039	The answer is that each level supplies indispensable conceptual content
  1040	that the others alone would obscure:
  1041	\begin{itemize}
  1042	\item The universal property (III) is what \emph{lets us recognise} an
  1043	NNO when we see one. We do not begin in HoTT and then notice that the
  1044	inductive type $\N$ is initial; we begin with the universal property as
  1045	a design constraint and use it to determine what the type-theoretic data
  1046	must look like.
  1047	\item Yoneda (IV) is the bridge that lets us speak of the universal
  1048	property \emph{relationally}, in any background category, not just inside
  1049	HoTT. The Yoneda embedding is what we use when working with categories
  1050	of geometric or algebraic objects (schemes, groups, manifolds) where the
  1051	HoTT presentation is not yet fully developed.
  1052	\item HoTT (V) is what \emph{internalises} the equivalence: it is the
  1053	formal system in which ``up to iso'' becomes ``equal.''
  1054	\item The categorical / structural perspective (VI) is the philosophical
  1055	commitment that drives the whole programme. Without it, we have no
  1056	reason to prefer one perspective over another; with it, we know what
  1057	we are doing.
  1058	\end{itemize}
  1059	
  1060	\subsection{Emergent properties from composition}
  1061	
  1062	The hierarchical composition produces emergent properties not visible at
  1063	any single level. We collect three.
  1064	
  1065	\begin{proposition}[Emergent property: contractibility of NNO]
  1066	\label{prop:emergent-contract}
  1067	The NNO is contractible (Paper~V, \cref{thm:nno-contr}) only because the
  1068	universal property (III) gives a unique map between any two NNOs, the
  1069	Yoneda embedding (IV) gives that this unique map is an isomorphism, and
  1070	the univalence axiom (V) promotes the isomorphism to a path. Set theory
  1071	(II) alone gives only that the von Neumann and Zermelo encodings are
  1072	isomorphic as Peano structures: the structure-of-paths between them is not
  1073	visible at the set-theoretic level.
  1074	\end{proposition}
  1075	
  1076	\begin{proposition}[Emergent property: function extensionality]
  1077	\label{prop:funext}
  1078	Function extensionality is provable from univalence
  1079	(\cite[\S4.9]{HoTTBook}, see Paper~V \S4). It is not provable
  1080	from intensional Martin-L\"of type theory alone, nor from the universal
  1081	property of any individual structure. It emerges from the composition of
  1082	universal property, Yoneda, and univalence.
  1083	\end{proposition}
  1084	
  1085	\begin{proposition}[Emergent property: synthetic homotopy theory]
  1086	\label{prop:synth-homotopy}
  1087	Synthetic homotopy theory (the development of algebraic topology entirely
  1088	inside type theory: $\pi_1(S^1) \iso \Z$, the Hopf fibration, the
  1089	Blakers--Massey theorem, etc.~\cite{LicataShulman,LicataFinster,ShulmanStrength})
  1090	is impossible at any of the levels (I), (II), (III), or (IV) alone. It
  1091	emerges from the composition: the categorical perspective (VI) supplies
  1092	the $\infty$-groupoid view, HoTT (V) gives identity types as path spaces,
  1093	the Yoneda principle (IV) recovers presentability, and the universal
  1094	property (III) gives recursion principles for the higher inductive types.
  1095	\end{proposition}
  1096	
  1097	\subsection{Commutativity of the four-functor diagram}
  1098	
  1099	\begin{theorem}[Commutativity]
  1100	\label{thm:commutativity}
  1101	The four functors of \cref{def:four-functors} commute up to canonical
  1102	natural equivalence: for every $X \in \U$,
  1103	\[
  1104	\mathsf{S} \circ \mathsf{H}^{-1} \circ \mathsf{Y}\,(X) \,\eqv\, \mathsf{UP}(X)
  1105	\]
  1106	in the appropriate sense, where the inverses are well-defined modulo
  1107	contractibility of fibers (which holds for finite-signature structures by
  1108	SIP).
  1109	\end{theorem}
  1110	
  1111	\begin{proof}[Sketch]
  1112	Each pair is treated by the corresponding transit theorem of
  1113	\cref{sec:transit}. The composition $\mathsf{S} \circ \mathsf{H}^{-1} \circ \mathsf{Y}$
  1114	takes a structure to its representable presheaf, transports back to a
  1115	type-theoretic representative, and projects to its iso-class; this is the
  1116	same data as the universal-property witness for $X$, after suppressing the
  1117	choice of representative. Naturality follows from the naturality of each
  1118	constituent.
  1119	\end{proof}
  1120	
  1121	\section{Naming the Correspondence: A Brief History}
  1122	\label{sec:naming}
  1123	
  1124	We pause to justify our terminology. The four-way correspondence has many
  1125	names; we explain why we settle on \emph{the univalent correspondence}.
  1126	
  1127	\subsection{Names in use}
  1128	
  1129	\begin{itemize}
  1130	\item \textbf{Curry--Howard correspondence} (binary): logic with type
  1131	theory. Curry (1934)~\cite{wadler-pat} observed it for combinatory logic;
  1132	Howard (1969)~\cite{wadler-pat} extended it to natural deduction.
  1133	\item \textbf{Curry--Howard--Lambek correspondence} (three-way):
  1134	adds category theory. Lambek (1972)~\cite{Lambek1972} showed that proofs of
  1135	intuitionistic propositional logic and typed combinators share the
  1136	equational theory of cartesian closed categories. This is the textbook
  1137	three-way name.
  1138	\item \textbf{Computational trinity} (Harper, c.\ 2011): logic, languages
  1139	(type theory), categories. Harper at CMU popularised the catchier name. A
  1140	four-way version is sometimes called the computational tetrad.
  1141	\item \textbf{Propositions-as-types} (Wadler 2015~\cite{Wadler2015}):
  1142	emphasises the central insight rather than the historical figures.
  1143	Extends naturally to ``propositions-as-types-as-spaces'' in HoTT.
  1144	\item \textbf{Univalent foundations} (Voevodsky, 2010~\cite{Voevodsky2010}):
  1145	the foundational programme built on the four-way correspondence. Homotopy
  1146	Type Theory (HoTT) is the formal system; the
  1147	HoTT Book~\cite{HoTTBook} is the canonical reference.
  1148	\end{itemize}
  1149	
  1150	\subsection{Why ``the univalent correspondence''}
  1151	
  1152	The phrase ``Curry--Howard--Lambek--Voevodsky correspondence'' is correct
  1153	but unwieldy. ``Propositions as types as spaces'' is pedagogically apt
  1154	but emphasises types and propositions over the unifying mechanism. We
  1155	prefer \emph{the univalent correspondence} for three reasons:
  1156	\begin{enumerate}
  1157	\item It \emph{names the unifying mechanism}: the univalence axiom is
  1158	what promotes the four columns from analogous to literally the same.
  1159	\item It is \emph{neutral across the columns}: it does not privilege
  1160	logic, types, categories, or spaces.
  1161	\item It \emph{credits the discovery}: Voevodsky's univalent foundations
  1162	project is the conceptual origin of the strong form
  1163	(\cref{prin:strong}).
  1164	\end{enumerate}
  1165	
  1166	We also use \emph{the $\infty$-groupoid correspondence} when emphasising
  1167	the underlying object, and \emph{structural univalence} when emphasising
  1168	the philosophical commitment of Paper~VI.
  1169	
  1170	\subsection{The deepest formulation}
  1171	
  1172	For the record, the most precise summary of the unified language is the
  1173	one from~\cite{Voevodsky2010,HoTTBook}, which we take as the deepest
  1174	formulation of the univalent correspondence:
  1175	
  1176	\begin{quote}
  1177	The unified language is \emph{synthetic homotopy theory} expressed as
  1178	\emph{dependent type theory}, with categorical semantics in
  1179	\emph{$(\infty,1)$-toposes}, interpreted logically via
  1180	\emph{propositions-as-types}. The whole package is
  1181	\emph{Univalent Foundations}.
  1182	\end{quote}
  1183	
  1184	\section{Applications and Outlook}
  1185	\label{sec:applications}
  1186	
  1187	We close with three applications that the univalent correspondence
  1188	illuminates.
  1189	
  1190	\subsection{Transcendentals \texorpdfstring{$\pi$ and $e$}{pi and e} in HoTT}
  1191	\label{sec:transcendentals}
  1192	
  1193	The transcendental numbers $\pi$ and $e$ enter the framework via Paper~V's
  1194	HIIT real numbers and Paper~III's universal-property characterisations.
  1195	
  1196	\begin{definition}[Cauchy real numbers, HIIT, Paper~V \S5.5]
  1197	\label{def:R-HIIT}
  1198	The type $\R_C$ of Cauchy real numbers is the higher inductive--inductive
  1199	type freely generated by:
  1200	\begin{itemize}
  1201	\item $\mathsf{rat}\colon \Q \to \R_C$;
  1202	\item $\mathsf{lim}\colon \prod_{f : \N \to \R_C}\, \mathsf{isCauchy}(f) \to \R_C$;
  1203	\item path constructors identifying $\mathsf{lim}\,f$ for any two
  1204	representations of the same Cauchy class;
  1205	\item the truncation that makes $\R_C$ a set.
  1206	\end{itemize}
  1207	\end{definition}
  1208	
  1209	\begin{theorem}[$\pi$ and $e$ in HoTT, after Paper~V \S10]
  1210	\label{thm:pi-e-hott}
  1211	There exist canonical inhabitants $\pi, e : \R_C$ characterised by the
  1212	unique-existence propositions:
  1213	\begin{itemize}
  1214	\item $\pi$ is the unique inhabitant of the truncated $\Sigma$-type
  1215	$\sum_{x : \R_C} (x > 0) \times (\sin x = 0) \times (\forall y \in (0, x).\, \sin y > 0)$;
  1216	\item $e$ is the unique inhabitant of the truncated $\Sigma$-type
  1217	$\sum_{x : \R_C} (\exp x = e) \times (\exp 0 = 1) \times (\exp' = \exp)$,
  1218	where $\exp$ is defined by power series.
  1219	\end{itemize}
  1220	The truncation makes the $\Sigma$-types mere propositions ($(-1)$-types),
  1221	hence inhabitants are unique up to a unique path.
  1222	\end{theorem}
  1223	
  1224	The univalent correspondence applies to $\pi$ and $e$ as it does to $58$:
  1225	each is identified with its representable functor, with its universal
  1226	property (\emph{half-period of} $\exp\colon \R \to S^1$, \emph{unique fixed
  1227	point of differentiation with} $f(0) = 1$), with its structural invariant
  1228	under field automorphisms of $\R$, and with its canonical HoTT term up to
  1229	path equivalence.
  1230	
  1231	\subsection{ContextFS as a structural-identity primitive}
  1232	\label{sec:contextfs}
  1233	
  1234	The ContextFS / typed memory project~\cite{KnowledgeBase2026} aims to
  1235	provide AI agents with persistent typed memory that respects structural
  1236	identity. The univalent correspondence supplies the theoretical foundation:
  1237	two memory entries should be considered ``the same'' iff they witness the
  1238	same structural invariant, iff they correspond to equal types in the
  1239	ambient universe, iff they have the same Yoneda profile in the category
  1240	of memory operations, iff they satisfy the same universal property.
  1241	
  1242	We sketch the architecture. A typed memory is a presheaf
  1243	$M\colon \mathsf{Op}\op \to \U$ on the category of memory operations, where
  1244	$\U$ is a univalent universe of types. The universal-property layer
  1245	specifies which operations any memory entry must support; the Yoneda
  1246	layer makes ``same memory entry'' precise as natural isomorphism of
  1247	presheaves; the HoTT layer makes ``natural isomorphism'' a path in $\U$;
  1248	the categorical/structural layer ensures that all of this is preserved
  1249	under change of universe (e.g.\ when the agent is migrated).
  1250	
  1251	\begin{principle}[ContextFS univalent slogan]
  1252	A memory entry is identified by its structural role, not by its storage
  1253	location.
  1254	\end{principle}
  1255	
  1256	This is precisely the univalent correspondence applied to a different
  1257	domain: instead of $58$, the entry is identified by what it does, not by
  1258	where it lives.
  1259	
  1260	\subsection{Directed HoTT and synthetic \texorpdfstring{$\infty$}{Infinity}-category theory}
  1261	\label{sec:directed}
  1262	
  1263	Riehl and Shulman's simplicial type theory~\cite{RiehlShulman} extends
  1264	HoTT with directed structure, allowing types whose paths are not
  1265	necessarily invertible. This is the language of synthetic
  1266	$\infty$-category theory: an $\infty$-category is a type with a chosen
  1267	directed structure satisfying the Segal and Rezk conditions internally.
  1268	
  1269	The univalent correspondence applies in the directed setting too, but
  1270	modulo a shift: ``equality of objects'' becomes ``isomorphism of objects''
  1271	(an invertible path), distinct from ``$X$ maps to $Y$'' (a possibly
  1272	non-invertible morphism). This is the right setting for
  1273	representation theory, where representations are functors that need not
  1274	be equivalences. We sketch the upshot in the language of Paper~VI: a
  1275	representation $\rho\colon G \to \mathsf{Vect}$ is a directed map; a
  1276	sub-representation is an iso-mono in the directed sense; the
  1277	representation theory of finite groups becomes a synthetic theory of
  1278	directed types over the classifying type $BG$.
  1279	
  1280	\subsection{Open problem: analytic number theory in HoTT}
  1281	\label{sec:open-langlands}
  1282	
  1283	The principal open problem the series acknowledges is that analytic number
  1284	theory --- Riemann zeta zeros, the Langlands programme, automorphic
  1285	forms~\cite{lurie} --- has not been substantially reformulated in HoTT.
  1286	Algebraic number theory and parts of arithmetic geometry (schemes, sheaves,
  1287	\'etale cohomology) admit $(\infty,1)$-topos and condensed mathematics
  1288	treatments~\cite{ShulmanInftyTopos} that connect cleanly to univalent
  1289	foundations. But $\zeta(s) = 0$ as a HoTT-native statement, with $\zeta$ a
  1290	HoTT-native object, remains unrealised.
  1291	
  1292	We frame this as the principal open question for the synthesis.
  1293	
  1294	\section{Open Problems}
  1295	\label{sec:open}
  1296	
  1297	We collect the open problems flagged by the topical papers and by the
  1298	synthesis.
  1299	
  1300	\begin{enumerate}
  1301	\item \textbf{Coalgebraic / final-object dual for transcendentals.}
  1302	Paper~III sketches the coalgebraic side: streams of digits, codata,
  1303	bisimulation as the corresponding induction principle. A complete
  1304	final-coalgebra characterisation of $\pi$ and $e$ that avoids the
  1305	inductive HIIT route is open.
  1306	\item \textbf{Connections to Langlands and analytic number theory.}
  1307	\Cref{sec:open-langlands}.
  1308	\item \textbf{ETCS, IZF, and FOLDS as alternative structural foundations.}
  1309	Paper~VI surveys ETCS; the relationship to Makkai's
  1310	FOLDS~\cite{Makkai1995} and to intuitionistic ZF (IZF) merits
  1311	development.
  1312	\item \textbf{Higher-categorical structure of NNO.} The contractibility
  1313	result (\cref{thm:nno-contr}) shows the type of NNOs is a contractible
  1314	type (a $(-2)$-type). The corresponding statement for $(\infty,1)$-NNOs in
  1315	$\infty$-toposes (Lurie's $(\infty,1)$-NNO~\cite{lurie}) is more delicate.
  1316	\item \textbf{ContextFS / type-memory as a structural-identity primitive.}
  1317	A formal account of typed persistent memory in HoTT, with structural
  1318	identity as the primitive notion, is the principal applied research
  1319	direction.
  1320	\item \textbf{Directed univalence.} Riehl and Shulman's simplicial type
  1321	theory has a partial directed univalence; a complete principle remains a
  1322	research target~\cite{RiehlShulman,CisinskiNguyen}.
  1323	\item \textbf{Cubical higher inductive--inductive types.} The Cauchy
  1324	reals construction of Paper~V is given in Book HoTT; a clean cubical
  1325	version (in Cubical Agda~\cite{CubicalAgda}) is in progress but
  1326	incomplete.
  1327	\end{enumerate}
  1328	
  1329	\section{Conclusion}
  1330	\label{sec:conclusion}
  1331	
  1332	We have argued that the question \emph{what is the natural number $58$?}
  1333	admits six progressively refined answers, and that the four most refined
  1334	answers are not analogous but \emph{literally the same} under Voevodsky's
  1335	univalence axiom. We named this identification the \emph{univalent
  1336	correspondence} (\cref{prin:strong}, \cref{prin:formal}), proved it as a
  1337	theorem in HoTT (\cref{thm:identity-of-perspectives}), exhibited the
  1338	hierarchical composition by which each level builds on the previous
  1339	(\cref{sec:diagrams}), and sketched applications to transcendentals,
  1340	typed memory, and directed type theory.
  1341	
  1342	The integer $58$ is, in the unified picture: a position in the initial
  1343	successor structure (Paper~III), a representing functor (Paper~IV), a
  1344	canonical term in a contractible type of NNOs (Paper~V), and an
  1345	invariant under all model isomorphisms (Paper~VI). These four
  1346	characterisations are four windows on a single $\infty$-groupoid, and
  1347	under univalence they are pairwise identified. The univalent correspondence
  1348	is the formal expression of the structuralist intuition that mathematical
  1349	objects are positions in structures, not substances; under Voevodsky's
  1350	univalent foundations, this intuition becomes a theorem of the
  1351	foundations themselves.
  1352	
  1353	The naive level (Paper~I), in which $58$ is a symbol on a page, remains
  1354	indispensable as the cognitive anchor that connects mathematics to human
  1355	practice. The set-theoretic level (Paper~II) remains the historical and
  1356	technical foundation for working mathematicians, and the von Neumann
  1357	encoding remains the textbook construction. But the univalent
  1358	correspondence asserts that these levels are not the locus of meaning:
  1359	the meaning lives at levels III through VI, where it is invariant,
  1360	relational, type-theoretic, and structural --- and, under univalence, all
  1361	four at once.
  1362	
  1363	We close with the canonical quotation that has guided the series, from
  1364	Paper~I:
  1365	
  1366	\begin{quote}
  1367	A number is not a thing. It is a constraint that every consistent
  1368	representation must satisfy, identified by a universal property and made
  1369	formal by its representable functor. Numerals (58, \textsf{LVIII},
  1370	$\,||||\,||||$) are syntax. Numbers are semantic invariants of the
  1371	categories that admit them.
  1372	\end{quote}
  1373	
  1374	\noindent The univalent correspondence makes this slogan a theorem.
  1375	
  1376	\section*{Acknowledgments}
  1377	
  1378	This synthesis owes its existence to the topical papers~I through~VI, to
  1379	the body of work surveyed in those papers (Lawvere, Mac Lane, Lambek,
  1380	Martin-L\"of, Voevodsky, Awodey, Shulman, Riehl, Lurie, Wadler, Harper,
  1381	the Univalent Foundations Programme), and to the philosophical lineage of
  1382	Frege, Benacerraf, Resnik, Shapiro, and Hellman. The naming
  1383	``univalent correspondence'' is internal to this project and is not
  1384	claimed to be original; the underlying mathematical content is due to the
  1385	named authors.
